  whatItMeans: {
    en: "New York's no-fault rules (Insurance Law Article 51, sections 5102 through 5108) often surprise people. After a crash, medical bills and some lost wages are covered by the injured person's own insurance — not the other driver's — up to the policy's Personal Injury Protection (PIP) limit. The basic PIP minimum is $50,000 per person. Who caused the crash does not matter for this coverage.\n\nWhat no-fault pays: reasonable medical bills tied to the crash, 80% of lost wages up to a monthly cap, and a small allowance for other reasonable costs (for example, a home aide or travel to appointments). The no-fault carrier pays the medical provider directly. The injured person is not billed for covered care.\n\nThe 30-day form (NF-2): the injured person files an NF-2 application with the insurance company within 30 days of the crash. Missing the 30-day window can cost the claim. The insurer has to give out the form on request. Providers also have short billing windows — usually 45 days — so prompt filing matters.\n\nLost wages: the 80% figure applies to gross wages. There is a per-month cap, and the carrier may ask for proof of income (pay stubs, W-2, or tax returns for self-employed workers).\n\nThe serious injury threshold (Insurance Law 5102(d)): a driver who is at fault can still be sued for pain and suffering, but only if the injury fits one of the listed categories. The list includes death, dismemberment, significant disfigurement, fracture, loss of a fetus, permanent loss of use of a body organ or member, permanent consequential limitation, significant limitation of use, and a '90/180' rule (an injury that keeps the person from most daily activities for at least 90 of the 180 days after the crash). Soft tissue strains and sprains without objective medical proof (MRI findings, nerve tests, orthopedic exam) usually do not meet the threshold.\n\nThe DMV accident report (MV-104): filed within 10 days if anyone is hurt or killed, or if property damage is over the state's set amount. The report goes to the DMV, not to the insurance company.\n\nWhen no-fault is denied: no-fault disputes go to the American Arbitration Association (AAA), not to court. The denial letter lists the reason and the arbitration deadline. A law firm can file the arbitration on a contingent fee basis.\n\nUninsured or hit-and-run driver: if the other driver has no insurance or leaves the scene, the Motor Vehicle Accident Indemnification Corporation (MVAIC) or the injured person's uninsured motorist coverage can step in. A short MVAIC claim window applies — usually 90 days — so quick action matters.\n\nChoice of doctor: no-fault does not force a specific clinic. The injured person picks any licensed provider willing to accept no-fault billing. The carrier can order an Independent Medical Exam (IME) to review continuing treatment. Missing an IME can lead to a cutoff, so the notice deadline needs attention.\n\nPolice report and evidence: photos, the police report, witness names, and medical visit dates help the claim. Statements to the other driver's insurance are not required and can be limited until the injured person speaks with their own carrier or a lawyer."
  },

